      <hedline>
        <hl1>What to Look For in a Senator From New York</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Linda Teran Strommen letter, prompted by Oct 22 editorial endorsement of Hillary Rodham Clinton, raises some questions about what kind of Senator she would be</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Hillary Clinton for the Senate'' (editorial, Oct. 22):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Hillary Clinton for the Senate'' (editorial, Oct. 22):</p>
        <p>I agree with you that a ''grasp of foreign and domestic policy, coupled with negotiating ability'' and ''commitment to one's home state'' should be requirements for election to the Senate.</p>
        <p>But Hillary Rodham Clinton's failed efforts to reform health care, her involvement in scandal in Arkansas and in the White House and her tendency to treat political opponents as enemies (concerns that you cite) should serve as warning that she lacks negotiating ability. And her pattern of serving her own agenda by avoiding the truth should serve as warning that her greatest commitment may be to herself.</p>
        <p>You hang your bet on Mrs. Clinton's ''instincts.'' The negative ethical legacy she leaves should call those instincts into question. She may be capable of growing beyond past mistakes, as you suggest, but why do you think she will?</p>
        <p>LINDA TERAN STROMMEN  Glen Head, N.Y., Oct. 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
